    <bioghist>
      <head>Historical Information</head>
      <p>In 1903, the Watchung Congregational Church emerged out of the need for a Congregational
        church around Watchung, New Jersey. The first service took place on January 18, 1903, in one
        of the four classrooms of Watchung School. In 1904 the church acquired a new property to
        hold services and Sunday School. By December 5th of 1905, the church was admitted into the
        association of Congregational Churches. In 1916 the church added to its property a community
        building which enabled educational, dramatic, and recreational pursuits.</p>
      <p>Shortly following a remodel of the church building in 1951, sometime between 1954 and 1965,
        members voted to become part of the United Church of Christ. After this vote, the diaconate
        became the single governing board of the church. On March 12, 1974, an electrical fire
        destroyed the sanctuary building, eventually resulting in a decision to dissolve the
        Watchung Congregational Church. Most members moved to the Union Congregational Church or the
        First Congregational Church, both in Montclair. When the property was sold in 1977, the
        proceeds of the sale went to those two congregations.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Contents</head>
      <p>This collection contains records from the Watchung Congregational Church including vital
        statistics, historical information, and administrative records.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement>
      <head>Arrangement</head>
      <p>The Watchung Congregational Church records have been arranged into the three series listed
        below. Within each series materials have been arranged first by topic, and then in
        chronological order by start date.</p>
      <p><emph render="italic">Series 1:</emph> Vital statistics, 1903-1975</p>
      <p><emph render="italic">Series 2:</emph> Administrative records, 1903-1976</p>
      <p><emph render="italic">Series 3:</emph> Historical information, 1934-1982</p>
    </arrangement>
